{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647673"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:47:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:47:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18259"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.09,0.39,0.43,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79296"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10973"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27139"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79296"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of pain on the inner side of her right thigh. The pain started after a soccer match. She describes the pain as sharp and exacerbated by running and changing direction quickly. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness along the medial aspect of the right thigh. The pain is reproduced with resisted adduction of the hip and flexion of the knee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely to be involved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adductor brevis","Adductor longus","Adductor magnus","Gracilis","Obturator externus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation suggests an injury to a muscle in the medial compartment of the thigh, which is responsible for hip adduction. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egracilis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is unique among the adductors as it crosses both the hip and knee joints, contributing to hip adduction and knee flexion. The pain on resisted adduction and knee flexion points towards involvement of the gracilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator externus\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in lateral rotation of the hip and is not typically associated with knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor brevis\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor magnus\u003C/strong\u003E are all involved in hip adduction but do not cross the knee joint, making them less likely to be the primary source of pain in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gracilis muscle is a superficial muscle of the medial thigh and is involved in hip adduction and knee flexion.","The gracilis is the only muscle in the medial compartment of the thigh that crosses both the hip and knee joints.","Understanding the anatomy of the medial thigh muscles is crucial for diagnosing and managing musculoskeletal injuries."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64618"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T08:05:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T08:06:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10973"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79296"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co